@node Rate commands
@section Rate commands

@findex read-aloud-extras-set-rate
The command @code{read-aloud-extras-set-rate} prompts for a new speech rate in words per minute, updates the @code{read-aloud-extras-rate} option, and applies the change to the active speech engine. This is useful when you want to jump to a specific rate rather than incrementing.

@findex read-aloud-extras-increase-rate
@findex read-aloud-extras-decrease-rate
For quick adjustments while listening, @code{read-aloud-extras-increase-rate} and @code{read-aloud-extras-decrease-rate} raise or lower the current rate by the amount specified in @code{read-aloud-extras-rate-change} (@ref{Rate options}). These are convenient when bound to keys so you can speed up or slow down without interrupting the reading flow.

Both commands call @code{read-aloud-extras-set-rate} internally, which in turn updates the engine configuration.

@node Setting the voice
@section Setting the voice

@findex read-aloud-extras-set-voice
The command @code{read-aloud-extras-set-voice} lets you pick a new voice for the speech engine interactively. On macOS, it runs @samp{say -v \?} to retrieve the list of installed voices, presents them with @code{completing-read} (showing both the voice name and its language), and stores your selection in @code{read-aloud-extras-voice} (@ref{Voice option}). The engine configuration is updated immediately so the next reading operation uses the new voice.

This command currently supports only the @samp{say} engine. Invoking it with a different engine signals an error.

@node Reading files
@section Reading files

@findex read-aloud-extras-read-file
The command @code{read-aloud-extras-read-file} reads the entire content of a file aloud. If called without an argument, it reads the file visited by the current buffer. You can also pass a FILE argument programmatically.

For PDF files, the command extracts the text using @code{tlon-convert-pdf} before reading. For all other file types, it reads the buffer contents directly. The extracted or read text is placed in a dedicated @samp{*read-aloud*} buffer, filled to remove excessive line breaks, and then read from the beginning with @code{read-aloud-buf}. The @samp{*read-aloud*} buffer is displayed so you can follow along.

@node Patched functions
@chapter Patched functions

@menu
* PDF selection patch::
@end menu

@node PDF selection patch
@section PDF selection patch

@findex read-aloud-this
The standard @code{read-aloud-this} command reads either the active region or the word at point. However, it does not recognize selections made in @samp{pdf-view-mode} buffers because PDF Tools uses its own selection mechanism rather than the standard Emacs region.

This package patches @code{read-aloud-this} via @samp{el-patch} to check @code{pdf-view-active-region-p} in addition to @code{use-region-p}. When a PDF selection is detected, it retrieves the selected text with @code{pdf-view-active-region-text} instead of @code{buffer-substring-no-properties}. This allows you to select text in a PDF and have it read aloud seamlessly, just as you would in a regular text buffer.

